******
[1] Georgia (Augusta)
Date: Mon 8 Sep 2014
Source: The Augusta Chronicle [summ., edited]
http://beta.mirror.augusta.com/latest-news/2014-09-08/augusta-sickness-likely-part-outbreak


A rash of seriously ill children in Augusta [Georgia] is likely part of a national outbreak of an uncommon strain of a summer virus, though it has not been confirmed by specific testing, a physician with Children's Hospital of Georgia said. "Since the rest of the nation is having a problem, probably we do have the same virus going around here but we haven't as yet typed it to confirm the specific outbreak strain", said Dr Chitra Mani, a pediatric infectious disease physician. "As of yet we don't know, but we are suspecting we are also in this outbreak."

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention announced Monday [8 Sep 2014] it is investigating 2 known clusters in Kansas City [Missouri] and Chicago [Illinois] of children hospitalized with severe respiratory infections from a virus called [human] enterovirus D68. The virus was confirmed by laboratory testing in 19 of 22 patients in Kansas City and 11 of 14 in Chicago, said Dr Anne Schuchat, director of the National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases at CDC. In more than half of those cases the children previously had asthma or wheezing. None of the children have died, she said. The CDC has been contacted by a dozen other states, including Georgia, who are investigating suspected clusters of infections from the virus, Schuchat said.

Enteroviruses -- there are more than 100 known strains [viral species] -- are a common cause of summer and fall illness and are usually not serious, Mani said. "They usually present with very mild infections, sometimes no symptoms," she said. "But this year [2014] we've had a number of respiratory illnesses that have been pretty severe, presenting mostly like asthma or asthma exacerbations." Enteroviruses cause 10-15 million infections in the US each year, mostly in children, Schuchat said. This particular strain has been known but it is not often seen, Schuchat said.

It would not be unusual to see the infection spread to other areas, but people can do their part to prevent the spread by practicing good hand hygiene. If a child is sick, frequent disinfection of commonly touched surfaces such as doorknobs and toys can help prevent the spread, they said.

[Byline: Tom Corwin]

