******
[2] Illinois (Chicago)
Date: Mon 9 Sep 2014
Source: Chicago Sun Chronicle [abridged & & edited]
http://www.suntimes.com/news/metro/29763718-418/rare-respiratory-virus-found-in-chicago-suspected-to-have-sickened-hundreds-of-children.html#.VBA8vi5dUmy


The CDC said [Mon 9 Sep 2014], 11 children in Chicago tested positive for a rare respiratory illness. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is investigating whether the virus, human enterovirus 68, or EV-D68 -- that has been reported in clusters in Illinois and Missouri -- is also making children sick in other states. EV-D68, a contagious virus that appears spread through close contact with infected people, causes mild to severe respiratory illness. There is no known treatment for [this virus infection]. In Chicago, 11 of 14 children who were tested had the illness [virus infection] but none of them died, the CDC said. On [23 Aug 2014], the University of Chicago Medicine Comer Children's Hospital reported to the CDC that it was seeing an increase in patients with severe respiratory illnesses, similar to what was reported in Kansas City.

When samples of patients from both Illinois and Missouri were taken by the CDC to further analyze them, 8 of the 11 Chicago patients confirmed to have EV-D68 also had a history of asthma or wheezing. 10 of 11 patients were hospitalised. 2 patients required ventilation for their respiratory distress. 9 were female, whose ages ranged from 20 months to 15 years old, the CDC reported in their Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report released on Monday [8 Sep 2014; available at http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm63e0908a1.htm?s_cid=mm63e0908a1_w ].

Loyola University Medical Center, Rush University Medical Center, and Ann & Robert H Lurie Children's Hospital said some patients have tested positive for enterovirus at their hospitals, but CDC has not yet confirmed whether they are enterovirus 68. While there are more than 100 types of enteroviruses, which are fairly common viruses of respiratory illness, EV-D68 is less common, the Illinois Department of Public Health said.

Meanwhile, a hospital in Quincy [southwest Illinois] stopped children under age 12 from entering its buildings after 70 children were found to be affected by an unknown virus during the Labor Day weekend [30 Aug-1 Sep 2014] in the area. The CDC could not be reached to confirm whether Quincy is one of the suspected clusters that CDC is investigating.

[Byline: Monira Thomas]

