[3] Treatment possibility?
Sate: Tue 9 Sep 2014
From: Jay Tureen <TureenJ@peds.ucsf.edu> [edited]


In the 1990s, pleconaril had demonstrated activity in enteroviral aseptic meningitis, with broad activity against a wide range of enteroviral isolates (reduced duration of [symptoms] by 1-2 days), but failed FDA approval because the clinical benefit was judged to be insufficient. My understanding is that it is currently in a phase 3 trial for enteroviral sepsis in neonates.

Is the current outbreak sufficiently severe to justify compassionate use requests for selected patients or, better yet, a hurry-up multi center rct [randomized controlled trial]? As we are early in this outbreak, this is the time to try what seems like a heavy lift.

--
Jay Tureen, MD
Professor of Pediatrics and Infectious Diseases
UCSF
USA
<TureenJ@peds.ucsf.edu>

[Can any reader respond to this comment? - Mod.CP

Human enterovirus D68 is a unique species of enterovirus that shares epidemiologic and biologic features with human rhinoviruses. It was first isolated in California in 1962 from 4 children with bronchiolitis and pneumonia, human enterovirus D68 has been reported rarely since that time and the full spectrum of illness that it can cause is unknown. The clusters of severe respiratory illness associated with human enterovirus D68 now observed in the USA previously occurred in Asia, Europe, and the United States during the period 2008-2010. Human enterovirus D68 infection was associated with respiratory illness.

It seems likely now that the severe respiratory infections in children are not restricted to the Midwest, but probably are occurring throughout the USA. So far human enterovirus D68 infections have been restricted to infants and young children. Further information would be welcomed. - Mod.CP]
